<br>
I have been posting about a topic on the Mage tower.  My posts have basically run into what I consider game design misunderstanding of some of the players that post on those mage boards.  I am seeking some support in some basic concepts of damage dealing and I know wizzies will be a good resource for this because it relates directly to what you guys do.<br>
<br>
Here is exactly what I said on the mage boards...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Ducalio stated: <br>
&quot;Some of you seem to think that a mage sitting medding is adding nothing to a group. This is patently wrong as Jobaber is still pumping out his 80+ dps, and any clicky DDs from horseback add another 25 while u med. <br>
<br>
Pet-canni is an awesome ability for regenning mana, but while you are regenning your DPS is ZERO.&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Ok, allow me to clue you guys into an idea here... <br>
<br>
1. A mage that adds a higher average of damage over time is probably a greater benefit for most exp groups. <br>
<br>
2. Average damage is total damage divided by total time. <br>
<br>
3. Huge burst damage with some downtime, IS better then consistant damage if the average damage over time is higher. <br>
<br>
A quick example:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Warrior A deals 80 DPS for 60 seconds. <br>
Wizard B deals 8000 damage in 2 nukes totaling 14 seconds of cast time at the end. <br>
<br>
Warrior A dealt 4800 damage at 80 DPS <br>
Wizard B dealt 8000 damage at 133.33 DPS <br>
<br>
Damage wise, the Wizard was more valuable to the group then the Warrior.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
4. Wizards and Mages are classes that are BUILT around Burst Damage. That is what we do. That is why we have a mana pool, and a Warrior does not. A mana pool is by game design a restricting factor that limits our damage output. <br>
<br>
5. If a mage can meditate while using boots of bladecalling and a pet doing 80 DPS, then that mage is sustaining 80 + 35 DPS. The Damage value he adds to the group is 115 DPS. <br>
<br>
Where as, if a mage can canni for mana, then drop nukes and the total averaged DPS over the full time is higher then 115 DPS, then the canni'ing mage adds more to his group. <br>
<br>
6. By choosing a mage as your character in this game, you already made a choice to play a class that does his damage in bursts. Mages are slightly different then wizards where we can maintain sustained DPS through pets. But it's important for any mage to realize that it's truely the overall DPS over time that matters the most.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This basic principle should be well understood by any wizard or mage.  I wanted to get some good wizzie feedback or support on this subject to help show the other mages what I'm talking about.  Can you guys lend a hand?<br>
==============================================<br>
EDIT: Your message board will not let me reply, so I'm editing in my reply to this post.<br>
<br>
I'm looking for wizards to back up the theory of burst damage versus sustained damage.  Wizards are all about burst damage, which is why I'm posting it here.  Because I know that many wizards will have that concept down.  I'm basically trying to show some mages that it's the overall damage divided by the overall fight time that matters the most.  Some mages cannot handle the thought of no pet while they use other tactics to recover mana for big nukes at the end.<br>
<br>
Goladus, lol.  Man,  you have more posts here on these boards then the mage boards!<br>
==============================================<br>
